title: For Sale:  M1 GARAND...5 Million GAP LETTER, Correct...C&R OK
postcontent: M1 Garand rifle. Manufactured by International Harvester in late 1955/early 1956, this is an uncommon variation referred to as the "Gap Letter" due to the wide spacing of the model designation on the rear of the receiver. The receiver itself was actually manufactured by Springfield Armory for IHC as indicated by the SA drawing number revision/heat lot marking on the right receiver leg. This rifle is was made close to the end of IHC production and falls well within the 5-million serial range, just a couple thousand guns from the last. This rifle is in excellent condition and is a "Correct Restoration" built with all the proper components for a 5-million range IHC. The barrel is a correct LMR, dated 5-55. Overall condition is excellent and the rifle retains 97-98% finish (the receiver has been reparkerized). There is no rust or any pitting. The stock is also correct and in excellent overall condition with some normal handling wear and scuffs but no cracks or repairs. The correct 1/2" DAS cartouche is present on the left side and there is a single circle-P firing proof on the wrist. No rebuild markings, nor any import markings are present. Mechanically excellent with a bright, sharp bore that shows very good throat erosion (1.6) and muzzle erosion (1.2) readings. This rifle was purchased from noted IHC researcher G. Wayne Bradford in 2009 and his data sheet will be included with the rifle. The data sheet lists all the component parts in this rifle
